
'''Koryun Nahapetyan''' ({{lang-ru|<U+041A><U+043E><U+0440><U+044E><U+043D> <U+0413><U+0440><U+0438><U+0433><U+043E><U+0440><U+044C><U+0435><U+0432><U+0438><U+0447> <U+041D><U+0430><U+0433><U+0430><U+043F><U+0435><U+0442><U+044F><U+043D>}}, 1926, [[Leninakan]] <U+2014> 1999, [[Moscow]]) was an [[Armenia]]n-[[Russia]]n painter-nonconformist, sociologist, philosopher and public activist, a participant of the [[Bulldozer Exhibition]]. He was a member of [[UNESCO]] International Federation of Painters. 

Nahapetyan was born in Hatsik village, near [[Leninakan]], [[Soviet Armenia]]. In 1950 he moved to [[Moscow]] and worked there in the [[ZiL]] factory. 

Nahapetyan finished the art school in Leninakan and [[Stroganov Moscow State University of Arts and Industry]], entered the post-graduate courses at VNIITE. In 1978 he founded the "20 Moscow painters" movement. 

In 1988 he became one of the founders of [[Karabakh Committee]] of Moscow. In 1999 Nahapetyan was killed in his studio.

